history.content:
Hi All,

I was in CCA last spring, and I took notes on the lectures until I dropped.  Dr. Pryby gave a few lectures on some of the prerequisites for that class which were helpful in either re-learning (as many of us are 15+ years out from some of) the prereq material or actually learning the prereq material for the first time. He said he was leaving the lectures up in the event that future students would find them helpful, so the links are:

Asymptotic Notation

(Proof By) Induction

Graph Refresher


And here is a link to my Google Drive for this course; you will find notes on Dr. Pryby's Asymptotic Notation refresher as well as notes on induction (proofs) within. 

You will certainly need to know the basics of asymptotic notation for the class; I am not quite sure of the extent we need to be able to prove things, but I would seriously consider looking at the induction proof video (as well as finding some material on proof by contradiction); better safe than sorry!

I linked the graph intro as well; CCA required that you know the basics of graphs, as these were assumed before even viewing the lecture.  I have no idea how it will be for this course, so I linked them in the event its similar (and if its not, just disregard).

Finally, I have a 'ML Math' document in my notes; I use that document for simply copying / pasting math symbols into Word (as it gets annoying hunting for them) as well as a brief explanation of a few of them (as, personally, when I started my GA Tech journey I was VERY rusty on the meanings of even some of the common symbols).  This one is a bit chaotic, but if it helps, great!


Wishing everyone the very best of luck,

Brent
